First, we can multiply the first equation by 2 and the second equation by 3 to make the coefficients of y equal:

\begin{align*} 4x - 6y &= -10,\\ 15x - 6y &= 12. \end{align*}

Next, we subtract the first new equation from the second new equation to eliminate y:

\begin{align*} 15x - 4x &= 12 - (-10)\\ 11x &= 22\\ x &= 2. \end{align*}

Now that we have the value of x, we can substitute it back into one of the original equations to find the value of y. Let's use the first equation:

\begin{align*} 2(2) - 3y &= -5\\ 4 - 3y &= -5\\ -3y &= -9\\ y &= 3. \end{align*}

Therefore, the solution to the system of equations is $(x, y) = (2, 3)$.

